    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-12-01T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-12-01T18:00:00-05:00" n="752"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d752">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">832.34/213: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Brazil</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morgan</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-12-01T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >December 1, 1931—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>92. Your 97, December 1, 11 a.m. The Department advised the Brazilian Ambassador
                    that in view of the provisions of Article 18 of the Washington Naval Treaty<note
                        n="7" xml:id="d752fn7">
                        <ref target="frus1922v01#pg_247">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1922, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 247</ref>.</note> which provides that
                    “each of the Contracting Powers undertakes not to dispose by gift, sale or any
                    mode of transfer of any vessel of war in such a manner that such vessel may
                    become a vessel of war in the Navy of any foreign power”, this Government could
                    not comply with Brazil’s request to sell it two light fast cruisers. He was
                    furthermore informed that Article 11 of the London Naval Treaty<note n="8"
                        xml:id="d752fn8">
                        <ref target="frus1930v01#pg_107">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>, 1930, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p.
                            107</ref>.</note> provides that the rules for disposal contained in
                    Annex 2 and Part 2 of the said Treaty shall be applied to all vessels of war to
                    be disposed of. The provisions regarding the removal of armaments and mutilation
                    of boilers, et cetera, set forth in section 5 of Annex 2 of the London Naval
                    Treaty regarding vessels retained for training purposes was also called to his
                    attention.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
